Introduction¶

Recorded human history has existed for 5000 years. By understanding the makeup of Pantheon, all persons today both young and old are enriched with the knowledge of global, scientific and cultural development of humanity. The meaning of the word Pantheon describes a group of particularly respected, famous, or important people. Over the course of human history there have been thousands of such individuals that have made an impact on society. Due to the information age that began in the latter part of the 20th century, people all over the world now have access to the same biographies of these individuals through Wikipedia in multiple languages. What was once information of limited accessibility and supply, shelved in remote libraries, is now conveniently made available through this medium.

Credit goes to the Macro Connections group at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology Media Lab and their Pantheon Project. Not only was a Pantheon index made available to the general public, but a popularity index was created as well. One "barrier to entry" to this content is the number of languages available for each article. This is a key measure in determining the popularity of individuals in the Pantheon. "The simpler of the two measures, which we denote as L, is the number of different Wikipedia language editions that have an article about a historical character. The more sophisticated measure, which we name the Historical Popularity Index (HPI) corrects L by adding information on the age of the historical character, the concentration of page views among different languages, the coefficient of variation in page views, and the number of page views in languages other than English." https://www.kaggle.com/mit/pantheon-project

The significance of historical figures may be debatable, but this report seeks to apply an objective measure of popularity to better understand how biographies of the Pantheon is being consumed in the current day and age. From Aristotle to Benjamin Franklin, Jesus Christ to Al Pacino, historical figures and their attributes will be measured with web analytics so that the reader may have insights into the following:

Research questions:

  • Which historic characters are the most popular?
  • When did they live and where are they from?
  • What factors could have generated their popularity?
  • Are there any observable trends in the categorical data provided?
  • What clusters and groupings are in the data? How do groups compare in popularity?

Analysis¶

Key analysis methods used in report:

  • Data Cleaning
  • Sorting and subsets of the data
  • Line, bar, and area plots
  • Chi-Square Test for Independence
  • Clustering

Data Cleaning¶

There are data issues so there are a few functions were create to help automate the cleaning process.¶

In [166]:
def fillNaN(df, dataType, defaultValue):
    for column in df.columns:
        if(df[column].dtype == dataType):
            df[column].fillna(value = defaultValue, inplace=True)

fillNaN() function takes three input paramters: data frame, data Type, and default value. This function is designed to replace the NaN value with the default value provided by the caller based on a matching data type. Below are examples on how the function can be called:

  • fillNaN(dfCleanData,'object', 'Unknown')
  • fillNaN(dfCleanData,'float64', 12345.888)
In [167]:
def removeCharFromNumber(inputValue):
    a = ''
    inputValue = str(inputValue)
    for char in inputValue:
        if char.isdigit() == True:
            a = a + char
    return a

removeCharFromNumber() function takes one inpurt parameter: string or text. This function iterates through, finds, and concatenates numbers together. This function is taking care of the hardcoded operation like, "dfCleanData['birth_year'].replace(['1237?'], 1237).replace(['530s'], 530)".

Below is the example on how the function can be called:

  • removeCharFromNumber('127?')
In [168]:
def convertToNumber(df, columns):
    for col in columns:
        for idx, value in enumerate(df[col]):
            try:
                int(value)
            except:
                newValue = ''
                newValue = removeCharFromNumber(value)
                if newValue != '':
                    df.loc[idx, col] = newValue
                else:
                    df.loc[idx, col] = 0

convertToNumber() function takes two input parameters: a dataframe and a list of column names. This function is designed to convert the values for each column from possible alpha-numeric to numeric and default the value to zero if nothing is there.

Example:

  • columnList = ['birth_year', 'latitude', 'longitude']
  • convertToNumber(dataframe, columnList)

What factors could have contributed the most to popularity?¶

According to the curators of the data:

"The simpler of the two measures, which we denote as L, is the number of different Wikipedia language editions that have an article about a historical character. The more sophisticated measure, which we name the Historical Popularity Index (HPI) corrects L by adding information on the age of the historical character, the concentration of page views among different languages, the coefficient of variation in page views, and the number of page views in languages other than English." https://www.kaggle.com/mit/pantheon-project

Because many of the variables are categorical, we will do a simple chi-square test between categorical or discretized metric variables to the discretized popularity variable.

In [200]:
pd.options.mode.chained_assignment = None  # default='warn'
# discretize birth_year
dfEval['disc_year'] = pd.cut(x = dfEval['birth_year'], bins = 10)
# discretize article_languages
dfEval['disc_language'] = pd.cut(x = dfEval['article_languages'], bins = 10)
# discretize page_views
dfEval['disc_page_views'] = pd.cut(x = dfEval['page_views'], bins = 10)
# discretize average_views
dfEval['disc_avg_views'] = pd.cut(x = dfEval['average_views'], bins = 10)
# discretize popularity
dfEval['disc_pop'] = pd.cut(x = dfEval['popularity'], bins = 10)
keepVars = ['sex','disc_year','continent','industry','domain','disc_language','disc_page_views','disc_avg_views','disc_pop']
dfEval = dfEval[keepVars]
dfEval.head()

In [202]:
from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency
from scipy.stats import chi2
# function to calculate chi-square and print results
def getChi2(var, df = dfEval):
    ct = pd.crosstab(df[var], df['disc_pop']) # contingency table
    stat, p, dof, expected = chi2_contingency(ct)
    # print chi-square value, degrees of freedom, and p-value
    print("Statistic: {:.2f} | DF: {:.2f} | p-value: {:.2f}".format(stat, dof, p))
In [203]:
# Test these variables
test_vars = ['sex','disc_year','continent','industry','domain','disc_language','disc_page_views','disc_avg_views']
print("Null Hypothesis: Variables are Independent from Discretized Popularity")
for var in test_vars:
    print(var)
    getChi2(var, df = dfEval)

It appears that for the variables selected above, all are statistically significant with p < 0.05. Given the specified degrees of freedom all respective chi-square values are well-above what would be a typical value in the chi-square distribution which explains the low p-values. Therefore, the null hypothesis of independence can be rejected.

The number of languages available for articles ranked the highest given its respective chi-square value of 8348. This supports the methodology used to construct the popularity measure. Other interesting variables include birth year, industry, and domain. These also exhibited very high chi-square values and merits futher investigation.

For the trend analysis below, it is important to disclaim that the Pantheon data set is not a time-series. The data is a cross-sectional (one-point-in-time) measurement of popularity and consists of only one record per individual. The measure of popularity can not be measured over time. Instead this focuses on contrasting proportional levels under discrete variables with the birth year of the individuals. As we move from ancient to contemporary figures, the change in the proportion of categories are observed.

In [204]:

For individuals born in the last 500 years, the proportion of those from Europe have trended lower and those from North America have trended higher. More individuals that are from Africa show up in the last 100 years.

DBSCAN¶

This is a density-based clustering technique that automatically detects a clustering. The default parameters were used:

  • eps (epsilon radius) = 0.5
  • min_samples = 5

Factors that drive popularity¶

According to the curators of the data, the popularity measure was constructed using a sophisticated combination of the number of available languages, age, and page views. In order to test other variables in the data, a chi-squared test for independence between discrete variables and discrete popularity was conducted. The null hypothesis states that the variables are independent from discretized popularity. The following discrete variables were tested to be statistically significant and not independent from discretized popularity:

  • sex
  • birth_year (discretized)
  • continent
  • industry
  • domain
  • article_languages (discretized)
  • page_views (discretized)
  • average_views (discretized)

The number of languages available for articles ranked the highest given its respective chi-square value of 8348. This supports the methodology used to construct the popularity measure for this data set. Other interesting variables include birth year, industry, and domain. These also exhibited very high chi-square values and merits futher investigation.

Trends over time¶

Categorical trends were observed over time using the birth year observation. In order to focus more deeply on a more contemporary group of individuals and the associated trends, a more recent interval of birth years (i.e. greater than 1500 AD) was used to subset the observations. The assessed categories were the continent in which the individual was primarily active, the industry the figure concentrated their work in, and the domain of concentration the figure is known for. Up until the 20th century, the proportions of continent varied wildly year-over-year. Over the past 500 years, the proportion of European figures have trended lower in contrast with those from North America that have trended higher. Top industries for people born in the last 500 years exhibited substantial variation and variety year after year up until 1900. Film and Team Sports can be seen trending higher. This may have been due to the explosion in the film industry during 20th century and televised sports. With the changes in technology, the advancements in the marketing of these mediums of entertainment may have also contributed to this rise. If industries associated with entertainment are excluded, there was an increase in the proportion of Government figures. Prominent individuals in Natural Sciences exhibited a substantial decrease in proportion from early 20th century levels. Interestingly there is a strong representation of Language from the mid-20th century to about 1980. The names of these individuals included Orhan Pamuk, Jostein Gaarder, Dan Brown, John Grisham, Steig Larsson, J. K. Rowling, Arturo Perez-Reverte, Clive Barker, Anna Politkovskaya, and Michel Houellebecq. These were novelists born between 1950 and 1980 that have experienced high popularity on Wikipedia. With regards to domain, Arts and Sports trended higher in the last 200 years and exhibited the highest proportion of popularity for individuals born in the latter 20th century.

Groupings of individuals¶

Clustering brought together very similar observations into 205 distinct groupings. The default parameters were used for a DBSCAN clustering technique (i.e. eps = 0.5 and min_samples = 5). Approximately 64% of the data could not be clustered by DBSCAN and thus were labeled as outliers. The average number of individuals to a cluster was 55. An inspection of the top 10 clusters in the data revealed them to be of sizes ranging from 4 to 13 individuals. A deeper look into the top 3 clusters revealed them to be famous French writers born in the 1800s, ancient biblical figures from Genesis, and important government figures from the times of the Roman Empire (born 3 BC - 419 AD). All of the top 10 most popular historical figures, such as Aristotle, Plato, Jesus, etc., were labeled as outliers possibly due to having little commonality with others to merit grouping into a cluster. Those individuals that were in fact clustered together shared common traits in popularity, location, occupation, industry and domain. The following plot shows the constrast in popularity between the top 3 clusters and the top 10 figures (outliers).

In [237]:
sn.boxplot(y=topSummary["popularity"], x=topSummary["cluster"])
plt.title("Popularity Distribution by Top 3 Clusters vs Top 10 Figures")
Out[237]:

Conclusion¶

Popularity can be seen through different perspectives. On one hand it was clear to see that the most popular figures in Wikipedia were those that ignited the growth of ancient civilization through religion, philosophy, and government. These "original gangsters" (individuals) stood apart from the thousands of others and were highly unique. Over time, a greater variety of individuals were introduced into the backdrop of human society and similarities began to emerge between them. Despite these similarities, many still stood apart in terms of the popularity of their biographies.

As the timeline moved from ancient to contemporary individuals, a greater diversity in the origin of these individuals and their fields of influence grew and exhibited consistency in representation year-over-year. In this day and age, a growing trend of individuals were associated with the arts, sports, and government. These individuals came from all around the world as opposed to a select few continents, namely Europe and Asia. It was clear to see the impacts of recent advancements in technology and globalization on the demography of the Pantheon as well as to industry. In particular, the industries that have the greatest share of the spotlight for contemporary figures is clearly in entertainment (i.e. Film, Sports, etc.).

The basis on which popularity was measured in this data set included the number of langauges that were available, the person's age, and the total number of hits the article received. However in the last 100 years, industry and domain are shown playing a larger role in shaping the individuals of the Pantheon. Consumers care a lot for popular culture. Will the popularity of ancient individuals become over-shadowed by contemporary figures? Will popularity itself be measured differently going forward? Perhaps popularity should be measured (or measurable) over time to support further analysis. The results in this report paint a clear picture that drastic change is to be expected in the next century.
